Diazonium ions are very reactive compounds containing an -N2+ group
When phenols are dissolved in sodium hydroxide (NaOH), a solution of sodium phenoxide is 
obtained
This solution is cooled in ice and cold diazonium ion is added to the sodium phenoxide
After the reaction has occurred, a yellow-orange solution or precipitate of an azo compound is 
formed
These are compounds in which two benzene rings are linked by a nitrogen bridge ^SPslKeq4

Phenols can undergo electrophilic substitution reactions when reacted with dilute nitric acid
 (HNO3) at room temperature to give a mixture of 2-nitrophenol and 4-nitrophenol
When concentrated HNO3 is used, the product will be 2,4,6-trinitrophenol instead
A hydrogen atom in the benzene ring is substituted by a nitro (-NO2) group
This is also known as the nitration of phenol

			"fontFamily": 1,
			"text": "Diazonium ions are very reactive compounds containing an -N2+ group\nWhen phenols are dissolved in sodium hydroxide (NaOH), a solution of sodium phenoxide is \nobtained\nThis solution is cooled in ice and cold diazonium ion is added to the sodium phenoxide\nAfter the reaction has occurred, a yellow-orange solution or precipitate of an azo compound is \nformed\nThese are compounds in which two benzene rings are linked by a nitrogen bridge",

			"locked": false,
			"text": "Phenols can undergo electrophilic substitution reactions when reacted with dilute nitric acid\n (HNO3) at room temperature to give a mixture of 2-nitrophenol and 4-nitrophenol\nWhen concentrated HNO3 is used, the product will be 2,4,6-trinitrophenol instead\nA hydrogen atom in the benzene ring is substituted by a nitro (-NO2) group\nThis is also known as the nitration of phenol\n",
			"rawText": "Phenols can undergo electrophilic substitution reactions when reacted with dilute nitric acid\n (HNO3) at room temperature to give a mixture of 2-nitrophenol and 4-nitrophenol\nWhen concentrated HNO3 is used, the product will be 2,4,6-trinitrophenol instead\nA hydrogen atom in the benzene ring is substituted by a nitro (-NO2) group\nThis is also known as the nitration of phenol\n",

			"baseline": 131,
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "Phenols can undergo electrophilic substitution reactions when reacted with dilute nitric acid\n (HNO3) at room temperature to give a mixture of 2-nitrophenol and 4-nitrophenol\nWhen concentrated HNO3 is used, the product will be 2,4,6-trinitrophenol instead\nA hydrogen atom in the benzene ring is substituted by a nitro (-NO2) group\nThis is also known as the nitration of phenol\n"
